column6: ECB raised raised rates and the spread jumped by 10 points
Aligning to the value reported by YCharts.
Currently at 2.10%, it should still be in the 1.50%-2.50% range in a two and a half week period.

The proposed budget deficit for 2023 is going to be 4.5%, not within the EU parameters (which are still suspended), but not to far off from Draghi's initial forecast. This could help keep the spread with the Bund to below 200 points.

My original belief that spread was going to grow after the summer was due to both concerns about the economic situation in the EU, and the fact that Italy was going to be governed by a far-right-populist party. Both beliefs were correct, but they rested on a basic asssumption that turned out to be completely faulty: spread is a good economic indicator for Italy because the Bund is stable and reliable.

About 1.9 points now and falling, apparently the ECB's promise of implementing a bond rate-harmonizing tool (i.e. buy Italian bonds, in plain) is now in full steam and the recent inauguration of a right wing-populist government doesn't destabilize the sentiment of international financial markets or the Northern Italian economic centers quite as much as expected, probably because LEGA has been present for long.
"Citi sees potential risks from centre-right win in Italian September elections

There's a substabtial likelihood that Mario Draghi will resign as Prime Minister of Italy. In such case, the extreme level of political fragmentation in the Parliament would probably not be able to find a successor, and new general elections may be called.

Seems like the ECB will try to actively manage things. A bit early to tell how well this will work, but I'm updating forecasts towards a narrower spread. https://www.reuters.com/markets/europe/exclusive-ecb-channel-cash-north-south-bid-cap-spreads-sources-2022-06-30/
